Absolutely, Rohan! You're looking at a clever use of GitHub Actions expressions to dynamically assign values based on the environment selected at runtime. Here's a breakdown of each line:


ğŸ”§ CLUSTER_NAME: ${{ github.event.inputs.environment }}-cluster
This sets the environment variable CLUSTER_NAME to something like:
	â€¢ dev-cluster if the user selects dev
	â€¢ test-cluster if they select test
	â€¢ and so on...
It appends -cluster to the environment name chosen via the dropdown input (github.event.inputs.environment). This is used later in your workflow when updating kubeconfig:
aws eks update-kubeconfig --name $CLUSTER_NAME



ğŸ” AWS_ROLE_ARN: ${{ secrets['AWS_ROLE_ARN_' + github.event.inputs.environment] }}
This line dynamically selects the correct IAM role secret based on the chosen environment:
	â€¢ If environment = dev â†’ it resolves to secrets.AWS_ROLE_ARN_dev
	â€¢ If environment = prod â†’ it resolves to secrets.AWS_ROLE_ARN_prod
ğŸ’¡ Why itâ€™s smart: 
You donâ€™t hardcode secrets. Instead, you create one workflow file and pull in the right credentials using the input selector. This keeps it DRY, secure, and scalable.


